1. 🌌 Abstract

The integration of Vision-Language-Action (VLA) foundation models into robotics promises unprecedented generalization, yet these systems remain black-boxes with no formal guarantees of stability or safety. Classical control theory provides rigorous certificates but cannot leverage semantic understanding. This thesis resolves this dichotomy through a unified mathematical framework that binds semantic reasoning to Lyapunov stability and safety constraints, while achieving computational efficiency through dynamic sparsity.

We introduce the Cytoskeletal Distributed Intelligence Architecture (CDIA) , a purely mathematical model of robotic cognition as a switching dynamical system on a time-varying graph. Inspired by the adaptive connectivity of biological microtubules, information pathways polymerize and depolymerize based on task demand, enabling provably stable computation without sacrificing representational power. The framework rests on three foundational pillars:

1. Geometric Perception: SE(3)-equivariant scene graph construction using Tensor Field Networks, ensuring all internal representations respect physical symmetries.
2. Dynamic Graph Cognition: A neural ODE governing both node states and graph topology, with proven contraction bounds that guarantee exponential convergence despite arbitrary task-driven reconfiguration.
3. Safety-Critical Control: A robust Control Barrier Function (CBF) shield that projects foundation model outputs onto the set of safe actions, providing hard guarantees of forward invariance under model uncertainty.

Core Contribution: This thesis provides the first formal proof that a learning-based, modular cognitive architecture can maintain contraction (exponential stability) and safety (constraint satisfaction) under arbitrary task-driven reconfiguration, while preserving SE(3)-equivariance throughout the perception-action pipeline. The framework is purely theoretical, establishing the mathematical foundations for safe, real-time embodied intelligence.

