2. 🎯 Problem Statement

2.1 The Safety-Generalization Dichotomy

Contemporary robotics faces a fundamental tension between semantically rich but unverifiable learning-based methods and provably safe but semantically blind classical control. This gap is particularly acute in the context of Vision-Language-Action (VLA) foundation models, which achieve remarkable generalization but offer no stability guarantees.

Paradigm Strengths Weaknesses
Classical Control (MPC, LQR, CBF) Formal safety/stability proofs No semantic understanding, poor generalization
Foundation Models (RT-2, OpenVLA) Rich semantic grounding, few-shot generalization Black-box, no certificates, computational intractability
Geometric Deep Learning (SE(3)-Transformers) Exploits symmetry, data-efficient Typically static, not integrated with control

The Gap: No existing framework simultaneously provides:

· Formal certificates (Lyapunov stability, barrier functions)
· Semantic reasoning (language grounding, task composition)
· Computational efficiency (sparse, O(N) scaling)
· Symmetry awareness (equivariance to rotations/translations)

2.2 Related Work and Our Contribution

To substantiate the "first formal proof" claim, we briefly survey related results:

· Contraction for switching systems: Early work by Lohmiller & Slotine (1998) established contraction for smooth systems; extensions to switching signals appear in [Angeli, 2002] and [di Bernardo et al., 2016] for piecewise-smooth systems, but these require the switching signal to be independent of state. Our work allows state-dependent switching (via $\dot{A}$) and proves contraction of the coupled dynamics.
· Contraction for modular/nonlinear systems: Aminzare & Sontag (2014) studied contraction in composite systems using synchronization conditions; Russo & di Bernardo (2009) considered contraction in networks of oscillators. Neither addresses adaptive topology that depends on node states.
· Safe learning with CBFs: Taylor et al. (2020) introduced episodic learning of CBFs; recent work by Hsu et al. (2023) and Yang et al. (2024) applies CBFs to learned policies, but treats the learning module as a black-box with bounded uncertainty. We explicitly characterize the uncertainty induced by the cognitive graph and prove that it remains bounded under the contraction conditions.
· Equivariant deep learning: SE(3)-equivariant networks (Fuchs et al., 2020; Thomas et al., 2018) have been shown to generalize zero-shot, but they are static. Our framework integrates equivariance with dynamic graph evolution while preserving the symmetry.

Thus, CDIA is the first architecture to combine:

· State-dependent topology evolution (cytoskeletal dynamics),
· Contraction guarantees for the coupled (Z, A) system,
· Robust CBF safety with explicit uncertainty bounds,
· Full-pipeline SE(3)-equivariance.

